\right).

(b) Using your parametrization in part (a), set up an 
integral for calculating the circulation of \vec{F} 
around C.

Note that this isn't a very pleasant integral to evaluate by hand (though we could easily find a numerical estimate for it). It's easier to find \int_C
abla f\cdot d\vec r as the sum \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r + \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r, where C_1 is the line segment from (0,0) to (1,0) and C_2 is the line segment from (1,0) to (1,\pi/2). Calculate these integrals to find the change in f.

So that the change in f = \int_C
abla f\cdot\vec r = \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r + \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r =

static.solution:
(a) The parameterization is \vec r(t) = (x(t),y(t)) = \langle t, \pi\,t/2angle. Then \vec r\,'(t) = \langle 1, \pi/2angle, so that \int_C
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1 \langle -6xe^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight), 9e^{-x^{2}}\cos\!\left(3yight)angle\cdot \langle 1,\pi/2angle\,dt = \int_0^1 \left(3\cdot 3 rac{\pi }{2}e^{-t^{2}}\cos\!\left( rac{3\pi t}{2}ight)-6te^{-t^{2}}\sin\!\left( rac{3\pi t}{2}ight)ight)\,dt. As noted, it's simpler to integrate on the pair of line segments C_1 from (0,0) to (1,0) and C_2 from (1,0) to (1,\pi/2). Parameterizing these in a manner similar to our parameterization of C, on C_1 we have \vec r = \langle t, 0angle and on C_2 \vec r = \langle 1, \pi t/2angle. Then \int_{C_1}
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1 0\,dt = 0, and \int_{C_2}
abla f\cdot d\vec r = \int_0^1  rac{\pi}{2}\,9\,e^{-1}\,\cos(3 rac{\pi}{2}\,t)\,dt = -3 e^{-1}, so that the change in f is (-3 e^{-1}) + (0) = -3 e^{-1}.
(b) The other way to find the change in f between these two points is to first find f. To do this, observe that -6xe^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight)\,\vec i + 9e^{-x^{2}}\cos\!\left(3yight)\,\vec j =  rac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(3e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight) ight) \vec i +  rac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(3e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight) ight) \vec j = 
abla \left(3e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight)ight). So one possibility for f is f(x,y)=e^{x^2}\sin y. Thus, \mbox{Change in } f igg|_{(0,0)}^{(1,\pi/2)} = 3e^{-x^{2}}\sin\!\left(3yight)  igg|_{(0,0)}^{(1,\pi/2)}= -3 e^{-1} - 0 = -3 e^{-1}.

li.p:
If S_1 is a rectangle with area 1 and S_2
is a rectangle with area 2, then 
\displaystyle 2 \iint_{S_1} \vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} 
= \iint_{S_2} \vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A}

statement.p:
Use the divergence theorem to calculate the flux of 
the vector field \vec{F}(x,y,z) = x^3 \vec{i}
+ y^3 \vec{j} + z^3 \vec{k}
out of the closed, outward-oriented surface S 
bounding the solid x^2 + y^2 \leq 4, \ 
0 \leq z \leq 6.

static.solution:
\mbox{div}\,{\vec{F}} = 4\cdot 2x + 5\cdot 2y + 5\cdot 2z. So, if W is the interior of the box, we have \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{W}(4\cdot 2x + 5\cdot 2y + 5\cdot 2z)dV = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{2}(4\cdot 2x + 5\cdot 2y + 5\cdot 2z)dz\,dy\,dx. Integrating through each of the integrals in turn, we have \int_{S}\vec{F} \cdot d\vec{A} = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{1} 4\cdot 2x\,z + 5\cdot 2y\,z + 5z^{2}\bigg|_{z=0}^{z=2}\, dy\,dx = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{1} 16 x + 20 y + 20\,dy\,dx = \int_{1}^{4} 16 x y + 10 y^2 + 20 y\bigg|_{y=0}^{y=1}\,dx = \int_{1}^{4} 16 x + 10 + 20\, dx = 8 x^2 + 10 x + 20 x\bigg|_{x=1}^{x=4} = 210.
Finding flux directly, note that on the faces x=4 and x=1 the normal vectors to the surfaces are \vec i and -\vec i respectively, so that \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 4x^{2}\,dy\,dz (where x is evaluated at 4 or 1), and similarly on y = 1 and y = 0, and z = 2 and z = 0, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 5y^{2}\,dx\,dz and \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \pm 5z^{2}\,dx\,dy, respectively. Thus on y = 0 and z = 0 the flux is zero. On the remaining faces, we have
(1) On x = 4, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{2}\,64\,dz\,dy = 128;
(2) On x = 1, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{2}\,4\,dz\,dy = -8;
(3) On y = 1, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{2}\,5\,dz\,dx = 30; and
(4) On z = 2, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = \int_{1}^{4}\int_{0}^{1}\,20\,dy\,dx = 60. Thus the total flux is the sum of these, \vec F\cdot d\vec A = 210.
